\b \cf0 What is Bwana?
\b0 \
\
Bwana is a manual page viewer for Safari. It parses man pages, located in /usr/share/man to provide pages in an easy to read format. The pages have links to other man pages, http and email references--the way man pages should have been from the start.\
\

\b How do I install Bwana?
\b0 \
\
To install just drag to your hard drive, may I suggest the Applications/Utilities folder.\
\

\b How do I use Bwana?
\b0 \
\
Bwana is used in Safari, by simply typing into the URL field "man:" followed by the man page you're looking for.  If you like a particular man page, for example arp(8) instead of arp(4), use: "man:arp.8".  Otherwise Bwana returns the first man page found, just like man in the terminal.\
\
You may also use "man://ls"\
\
You may also call an index of all pages on your drive by simply leaving it blank: "man:".  "man:index_refresh" refreshes the index page instead of using the cache. There is a link to the  index on the header of every page created by Bwana.\
\
To search the the index for an expression use man:foo.?\
\
You can use Bwana from the terminal with "open -a Bwana man:ls" will open in the last browser that Bwana displayed a man page in or "open -a Safari man:ls" to specify a browser.\
\
Also for advance customisation if you wish to open man pages in tabs or new windows, or any other kind of behaviour, you can do so by changing the scripts.strings file inside the Bwana resource folder.  I have added two alternative script files for Safari for a new window or tabs, feel free to use these scripts written by Cameron Hayne.\
\

\b What about additional man paths?
\b0 \
\
To add man paths to Bwana append them to your bash login shell environment variable $MANPATH. Open the file ".profile"  in your home folder and add the line "export MANPATH=$MANPATH:/new/path/to/man".  \
\
Another option (the only option if your not using the bash shell) is to add them to your system in the man configuration file located in Leopard at /private/etc/man.conf (prior systems at  /usr/share/misc/man.conf). The format for including another path is a new line with: MANPATH /usr/share/mynewpath. \
\
To open a temporary page in a path you don't want to include as part of your man configuration then pass the entire path to Bwana with man:/Users/myuser/Desktop/mansource.1 or man:///Users/myuser/Desktop/mansource.1.\
\

\b Bwana on the Web
\b0 \
\
You can use "man:example" links in your web pages. Users with Bwana installed will be able to call up the appropriate page.  (There are similar programs for Linux and UNIX users that will also respond to "man:" links)  Feel free to provide links to Bwana for Mac visitors without a "man:" viewer.  Bwana is free, to make cyber space a slightly happier place. It's also open source under the MIT license, if you make any changes let us know so we can make Bwana better.\
\

\b What does Bwana mean?
\b0 \
\
Bwana means "Man" or "Sir" in Swahili.  We thought it a fitting name for man pages that integrate with Safari. The Bwana icon although crude is a copy of one of the earliest rock drawings of man by man, found in Namibia.\
